    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Indemnification, in plain English, is a clause where one party agrees to cover the losses or damages of the other party if a specific event happens. It essentially means you are agreeing to protect the other party from certain legal or financial risks. If, for example, a third party sues because of something you did under the contract, the indemnification clause dictates who pays the legal fees and any resulting judgment. It's a risk-shifting agreement, so you should read carefully what triggers the obligation.",
